@report{rae2024North,
  title = {North {{American Bat Monitoring Program}} in {{British Columbia}}: 2023 {{Data Summary}} and {{Activity Trend Analyses}} (2016-2023).},
  author = {Rae, Jason and Lausen, Cori L},
  date = {2024-04},
  institution = {Wildlife Conservation Society of Canada},
  abstract = {The North American Bat Monitoring (NABat) program is a multi-agency initiative administered by the US Geological Survey (USGS). Since 2016, Wildlife Conservation Society (WCS) Canada has coordinated and implemented the program in British Columbia.  These efforts aim to gather essential baseline data to guide conservation of bats in both immediate and long-term management decisions across spatial scales, ranging from local and regional to continental levels. Through partnerships and engagements with bat biologists and naturalists across the province, NABat is establishing species diversity and relative activity/abundance data before, during and after white-nose syndrome (WNS) arrives in the province. WNS is a deadly fungal disease that has been decimating hibernating bat populations as it spreads from the point of initial discovery in New York State and from a secondary point introduction in Washington State. The arrival of the fungus that causes WNS in BC was first confirmed last year from guano samples collected near Grand Forks in 2022.   In this report we describe the acoustic NABat monitoring program and summarize the acoustic NABat data in BC.  Specifically, we provide:  •	locations and site information from all grid cells in BC (Appendix 4); •	summaries of the total number of grid cells sampled by year and annual sample sizes (Table 2, Table 3); •	tabulated acoustic identification results from both stationary and transect sampling (Table 4), species activity levels adjusted by sampling effort, by detector/transect and cell (Appendix 6);  •	a summary of acoustic identifications and activity trend analyses; •	discussion of results and the monitoring process, including challenges, solutions, successes, significance of results, and lessons learned; and •	future directions including target species and further inventory efforts.   We summarize bat acoustic activity recorded by stationary detectors and mobile transects from the eighth year of NABat surveys in BC. Since its inception, NABat in BC has monitored bat activity in 65 grid cells, only two of which are now considered ‘abandoned’ cells where we and our grid leaders have no plans to resume monitoring in future years. In 2023 we surveyed 56 of 63 ‘active’ grid cells, 20 of which are part of the original 22 grid cells that comprised the BC NABat monitoring program in 2016 when it first launched. Seven of the 63 active grid cells were not monitored in 2023 due to reasons ranging from lack of local staff capacity to severe wildfires in Northern BC in early summer 2023.  Of the 56 grid cells monitored in 2023, data from 50 grid cells were submitted to us by partners in time for inclusion in this report and the 2023 cumulative analyses. We detected all species of bats known to occur in BC. Below, we describe species distribution changes, activity trend analyses, and provide updated maps. These data provide baselines for pre-WNS bat distribution and activity in the province that can be used to gauge future changes through ongoing trend analyses. Acoustic recording is one of several tools used to inventory bats. Because bat species can have substantial overlap in acoustic signatures, species confirmation in some locations, is needed before species presence should be considered confirmed – particularly when out-of-range species have been detected. For example, although acoustically detected in some SW BC grid cells, Mexican Free-tailed Bats have yet to be confirmed in the province. Similarly, Canyon Bats have been recorded at some detectors in the Okanagan and Boundary regions in past years, but this species has yet to be confirmed north of the Washington border.  In these two cases, either genetic samples of guano, or capture would be needed to confirm presence in B.C. More readily identifiable species (those that frequently produce diagnostic recordings)   We also present a summary of modelling results from our statistical analyses examining trends in relative acoustic activity and relative abundance data at regional and provincial scales. Our statistical models from stationary data have produced trends for 12 of 15 resident species of bats, those with species-level acoustic identifiability and detectability across the province to sufficiently fit a model. Species that generated fewer than 200 recordings per year or were detected in fewer than 5 grid cells across the province each year were not included for modelling. Our transect models are processed with the assumption that each bat recorded is a unique individual because the car is travelling slightly faster than most bats would typically fly. This enables us to estimate relative abundance from those data. Because there are fewer species detected on transects, we estimated relative abundance across BC for only 8 species of bats.  Our models assume species activity rates are representative of species’ relative abundance and are therefore likely to be sensitive indicators of changes in bat populations in specific regions that could inform management decisions, particularly when combined with other sources of data. More years of data, more grid cells, and the incorporation of additional informative covariates that account for inter-annual variation should continue to improve statistical power for future trend analyses.  In 2022 we partnered with Alaska Department of Fish and Game to establish the BC-SE\_AK (Southeast Alaska) NABat Hub. This year WCS Canada has initiated the process of transferring leadership of this hub to Biodiversity Pathways (BDP). Plans are being developed for BDP to further expand our hub into the new North Northwest NABat Hub that will incorporate Southeast Alaska, British Columbia, and Alberta. This expanded Hub will enable efficient coordination of efforts and resource sharing across all three jurisdictions, pooling data to improve overall trend estimates, and data management and protocol efficiencies. WCS Canada will train the new Hub leadership and continue participation as a member of the new Hub steering committee in the future.}
}

